<h3><a name="S2"></a><span>Status</span></h3>
A tab has 2 main statuses:
<table class="table table-bordered table-striped">
         <thead>
            <tr>
               <th>Status</th>
               <th>Description</th>
            </tr>
         </thead>
         <tbody>
            <tr>
               <td>Default status</td>
               <td>The tabs can be clicked to view its content. There is css effect when mouse hover on it.</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
               <td>Being viewed status</td>
               <td>The tab is being viewed, its content is displayed. There is no css effect when mouse hover on it.</td></td>
            </tr>
           </tbody>
      </table>
      <h3><a name="S3"></a><span>Rules</span></h3>
        <table class="table table-bordered table-striped">
           <tbody>
            <tr>
               <td>TR-01</td>
               <td>Different tabs have the same css style</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
               <td>TR-02</td>
               <td>Tab content is displayed in the same area</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
               <td>TR-03</td>
               <td>Tab title is limited with 20 words</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
               <td>TR-04</td>
               <td>By default, there is only one tab being viewed at once</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
               <td>TR-05</td>
               <td>No page load when a tab is clicked</td>
            </tr>
         </tbody>
      </table>

     <h3><a name="WUTP"></a><span>Why to Use This Pattern?</span></h3>
     <p>Tabs allow to group a long page content logically that makes easy for users to view and interact with.
Besides, the same usage makes the consistency among products in the way displaying data in pages or pop-ups.
</p>

